exports[`explain (golden-file done-conditions for 4.2) > explain of a gate threshold golden file: qualitative gate rendering 1`] = `
"## queue.streaming-semantics-gate

**Category:** queue
**Variable:** streaming-semantics-gate
**Description:** Streaming semantics — consumer groups with replay, offset management, Kafka Streams/ksqlDB/Connect, log-compaction/retention config — are a qualitative gate checked before any throughput number.
**Observability:** static
**Live source:** none — not resolvable by live mode

**Comparison:** qualitative gate — fires \`keep\` when any signal is present
- fromBeginning: true
- seek(
- multiple distinct groupIds consuming one topic
- retention/compaction config present

**Assumption:** none

**Sources:**
- https://www.morling.dev/blog/you-dont-need-kafka-just-use-postgres-considered-harmful/ (independent — mere groupId presence must NOT fire this gate — kafkajs requires one on every consumer)

**Failure mode (keep):** replaying history or fanning one event out to N independent consumer groups needs a log, not a table — Postgres queues are the wrong shape regardless of throughput
"
`;

exports[`explain (golden-file done-conditions for 4.2) > explain of a reference threshold golden file: value + unit, no bands/gate 1`] = `
"## cache.postgres-unlogged-read-throughput

**Category:** cache
**Variable:** postgres-unlogged-read-throughput
**Description:** Reference benchmark figure for Postgres UNLOGGED-table cache reads.
**Observability:** static
**Live source:** none — not resolvable by live mode

**Comparison:** reference figure (not a decision boundary)
- 16,000 ops/sec at ~0.7ms

**Assumption:** none

**Sources:**
- https://dev.to/raphaeldelio/can-postgres-replace-redis-as-a-cache-2ne1 (independent)
"
`;

exports[`explain (golden-file done-conditions for 4.2) > explain queue.est-peak-msgs-sec golden file: value, comparison, sources+grade, assumption, failure mode 1`] = `
"## queue.est-peak-msgs-sec

**Category:** queue
**Variable:** est-peak-msgs-sec
**Description:** Estimated peak messages/sec, from provisioned worker capacity (replicas x concurrency x general.est-peak-jobs-per-worker-slot).
**Observability:** estimated
**Live source:** incumbent-only — requires Redis INFO / consumer-lag / Kafka broker _stats — out of v1 scope; what to look at: consumer lag and messages/sec on the broker

**Comparison:** range bands
- **consolidate**: value < 1,000 → \`skip-locked\`
- **borderline**: 1,000 ≤ value < 10,000
- **keep**: value ≥ 10,000

**Assumption:** none

**Sources:**
- https://medium.com/@the_atomic_architect/postgresql-replaced-my-message-queue-and-taught-me-skip-locked-along-the-way-87d59e5b9525 (independent — SKIP LOCKED sustains 1k-10k jobs/sec)
- https://gist.github.com/chanks/7585810 (independent — classic Que benchmark, ~10k jobs/sec)
- https://legacy.tembo.io/blog/mq-stack-benchmarking/ (vendor — pgmq benchmarked >30k msgs/sec on 16 vCPU)
- https://kmoppel.github.io/2025-11-13-postgres-kafka-and-event-queues/ (independent — MVCC/WAL bloat risk when consumer transactions run long)

**Failure mode (keep):** consumer transactions at this rate cause MVCC bloat and WAL pile-up; Kafka's batching/sequential I/O is built for the range above ~10k msgs/sec
"
`;
